WEBVTT

00:09.760 --> 00:11.971
This was all The Crow carried?

00:11.971 --> 00:14.306
Assassins travel light.

00:19.228 --> 00:22.356
One-way to Carreras.

00:22.356 --> 00:24.817
Do you think Hitler is there?

00:24.817 --> 00:28.612
Klaus said The Crow is
the only one who sees him.

00:28.612 --> 00:30.990
So we go?

00:30.990 --> 00:32.950
Go scout.
See what you find.

00:32.950 --> 00:35.536
Take the counterfeiter
and the actor.

00:35.536 --> 00:37.246
Ima, the actor is a liability.

00:37.246 --> 00:38.414
He's right for this.

00:38.414 --> 00:39.707
And if he doesn't come back, well,

00:39.707 --> 00:41.625
that's the cost
of what we do.

00:41.625 --> 00:43.836
The cost of what we do?

00:43.836 --> 00:45.755
You'll stay here with me.

00:45.755 --> 00:47.047
Oh, Ima...

00:47.047 --> 00:48.591
You will stay here!

00:52.261 --> 00:54.346
Be discreet.

00:54.346 --> 00:57.641
Hitler is in our fucking reach.

01:00.603 --> 01:02.855
Careful out there.

01:05.649 --> 01:07.193
I'll make a mess of 'em.

01:08.986 --> 01:10.905
Not of the Jews.

01:13.032 --> 01:16.702
Of Joe.

01:16.702 --> 01:19.413
When he sees them,
you can't know for certain

01:19.413 --> 01:22.208
how he'll respond.

01:22.208 --> 01:24.126
Loyalty can be buried deep.

01:27.379 --> 01:29.590
So, too, can love.

01:30.591 --> 01:32.885
Let's go kill
some Jews, boys.

04:06.038 --> 04:08.582
<i>I want to thank one
person without whose generosity</i>

04:08.582 --> 04:09.667
<i>none of this would be possible:</i>

04:09.667 --> 04:12.002
Meyer Offerman.

04:12.002 --> 04:14.505
Meyer, come up here, please.

04:14.505 --> 04:16.882
Oh...

04:16.882 --> 04:18.384
Please.

04:18.384 --> 04:21.303
Thank you.
Thank you very much.

04:21.303 --> 04:24.473
I, I always knew
I'd make it to the stage.

04:24.473 --> 04:26.892
Thank you very much.

04:26.892 --> 04:30.980
Well, I'm... I'm very pleased

04:30.980 --> 04:32.982
we could all be here together.

04:32.982 --> 04:37.486
Although I'm afraid,
uh, we may lose

04:37.486 --> 04:40.948
some of these, uh,
wonderful Jewish scholars

04:40.948 --> 04:42.866
to the Great White Way now.

04:42.866 --> 04:44.868
I don't know,
I'm a little worried.

04:44.868 --> 04:48.497
Should I be worried about this?

04:48.497 --> 04:50.582
For your generous mitzvah,
we thought it fitting

04:50.582 --> 04:54.461
to commemorate this as
the Meyer Offerman Theater

04:54.461 --> 04:58.048
of Temple Israel.

04:58.048 --> 05:00.050
Thank you

05:00.050 --> 05:01.802
<i>very much.</i>

05:01.802 --> 05:03.846
They want $30 million, huh?

05:05.264 --> 05:08.308
Well, you tell them that we'll
gladly increase production.

05:08.308 --> 05:09.685
What is that?

05:09.685 --> 05:12.104
Yeah, let me call you back.

05:13.147 --> 05:14.940
What the...?
Edward!

05:16.358 --> 05:19.236
What the...?
Where the fuck is he?

05:23.115 --> 05:25.325
Oh!

05:33.709 --> 05:34.835
It's...

05:36.378 --> 05:37.504
You.

05:44.136 --> 05:45.304
 <i>Please just
l-let me explain.</i>

05:45.304 --> 05:47.848
A couple of days ago,
I saw the name

05:47.848 --> 05:49.850
of a woman on our
telephone pad

05:49.850 --> 05:51.977
and an address in L.A.

05:51.977 --> 05:53.353
So, of course, I got a feeling,

05:53.353 --> 05:56.982
and I called Professor Morél's
office.

05:56.982 --> 05:59.026
He said there was
no trip to Israel.

05:59.026 --> 06:02.946
And then I called American
Express, and there it was.

06:02.946 --> 06:05.199
A charge for two weeks

06:05.199 --> 06:08.077
at the Palladio Hotel
in Buenos Aires.

06:09.453 --> 06:14.083
So I had a few drinks,
and, uh, next thing I knew,

06:14.083 --> 06:16.335
I was on a plane here.

06:18.545 --> 06:21.673
It really was, like,
right out of a bad movie.

06:23.509 --> 06:26.678
So, how's the room service?

06:26.678 --> 06:28.514
- Clara.
- Who's Millie, Sam?

06:37.397 --> 06:39.900
Are you in love with her?

06:43.112 --> 06:44.863
She's an FBI agent.

06:44.863 --> 06:46.198
An FBI agent?

06:46.198 --> 06:48.867
She investigated
my grandmother's murder.

06:48.867 --> 06:51.703
I flew to Los Angeles
to see her

06:51.703 --> 06:54.957
because I found something
about someone...

06:54.957 --> 06:59.628
Someone I had been looking for
for a long time.

06:59.628 --> 07:03.090
And that person is here
in Argentina.

07:03.090 --> 07:04.174
Who?

07:05.843 --> 07:08.512
My grandmother's sister Chava.

07:08.512 --> 07:11.098
My <i>safta</i> thought that she was
the only one in her family

07:11.098 --> 07:12.391
who survived the war.

07:12.391 --> 07:15.602
Well, it turns out, I was
doing my thesis research,

07:15.602 --> 07:19.189
and I came across the name
of a survivor:

07:19.189 --> 07:20.566
Chava Apfelbaum.

07:20.566 --> 07:22.693
I looked deeper
and I discovered that

07:22.693 --> 07:24.403
she had escaped the camps,

07:24.403 --> 07:27.030
and so I flew to Los Angeles
to ask Millie for help.

07:27.030 --> 07:30.075
She discovered that
she was alive, living here.

07:30.075 --> 07:31.660
So I came to find her.

07:33.912 --> 07:35.747
Why didn't you tell me?

07:35.747 --> 07:37.124
It was stupid.
I fucked up.

07:37.124 --> 07:39.251
I'm sorry, it's just I-I...

07:39.251 --> 07:40.627
I wanted to make sure
that it was real.

07:40.627 --> 07:44.590
I-I'm-I'm sorry.
I-I-I screwed up.

07:44.590 --> 07:48.177
I know I'm never going
to fill the void

07:48.177 --> 07:51.722
that your grandmother left, but...

07:51.722 --> 07:56.059
if you let me live in it
with you,

07:56.059 --> 07:58.562
it won't feel as big.

07:58.562 --> 08:00.480
I love you.

08:01.690 --> 08:02.941
I'm sorry.

08:06.486 --> 08:09.323
I'm so sorry. Okay?

08:14.661 --> 08:16.830
Well, I want to meet her.

08:16.830 --> 08:18.415
- You want to meet her?
- Yeah.

08:18.415 --> 08:19.791
- No.
- What?

08:19.791 --> 08:21.793
No, I don't think...
She's...

08:21.793 --> 08:23.003
- What?
- Weird.

08:23.003 --> 08:24.963
I mean, being weird is
sort of part

08:24.963 --> 08:26.173
of being a great-aunt, innit?

08:26.173 --> 08:27.674
Uh...

08:27.674 --> 08:29.843
- Lunch today.
- Today?

08:29.843 --> 08:31.595
- Yeah.
- I don't even think
that's possible to...

08:31.595 --> 08:34.431
- Not a question, love.
- Lunch sounds nice.

08:34.431 --> 08:36.225
Hmm.

08:59.373 --> 09:01.208
You think I don't know
the cost it takes

09:01.208 --> 09:03.752
to lie to those you've loved
for years?

09:03.752 --> 09:07.130
I was the one who lied to Ruth.

09:07.130 --> 09:09.883
Knowing what I knew,
keeping it from her.

09:09.883 --> 09:13.220
So don't you dare woe poetic
when it was me

09:13.220 --> 09:17.474
who carried the weight
for you, Ima.

09:22.646 --> 09:26.316
We all have a right
to our own pasts, Rebecca.

09:27.901 --> 09:31.154
I do to mine,
as you do to yours.

09:35.409 --> 09:37.995
I've found him.

09:37.995 --> 09:40.080
It's him.

09:44.084 --> 09:45.627
It's not.

09:45.627 --> 09:47.546
It is.

09:50.757 --> 09:53.760
- It's not.
- It is.

09:55.012 --> 09:56.930
What did I tell you
the first day we met?

09:56.930 --> 09:59.182
I promised you I would find him.

09:59.182 --> 10:01.184
It took a while.

10:01.184 --> 10:03.395
But I always deliver

10:03.395 --> 10:05.397
on my promises.

10:09.484 --> 10:11.528
Thank you, Ima.

10:11.528 --> 10:14.239
Thank you, thank you.

10:15.240 --> 10:17.326
Thank you, thank you,
thank you...

10:22.497 --> 10:23.874
You should go.

10:23.874 --> 10:26.335
Georges and the others
will be gone most of the day.

10:26.335 --> 10:28.462
This might be
the only chance you ever have.

10:30.130 --> 10:32.132
Thank you.

10:41.725 --> 10:43.935
<i>I am not that man.
You are not a Christian.</i>

10:43.935 --> 10:45.187
<i>You are.</i>

10:45.187 --> 10:46.438
<i>- I won't.
- You will.</i>

10:46.438 --> 10:48.190
<i>You are
not a woman of God.</i>

10:49.858 --> 10:51.860
<i>I am not that man.</i>

11:02.120 --> 11:04.122
<i>Hello.</i>

11:04.122 --> 11:05.916
<i>Hello?</i>

11:05.916 --> 11:08.460
Danny?

11:08.460 --> 11:10.128
<i>Millie.</i>

11:10.128 --> 11:12.381
<i>Millie, where the fuck
have you been?</i>

11:12.381 --> 11:14.049
I had to get out of L.A.
for a couple days.

11:14.049 --> 11:15.926
<i>Millie, listen...</i>

11:15.926 --> 11:18.053
Listen, um...

11:18.053 --> 11:20.430
You write in your book...

11:20.430 --> 11:23.558
that, uh, Agent Melanie, uh...

11:23.558 --> 11:26.061
whatever the fuck...

11:26.061 --> 11:28.855
she can do no wrong,
and that if she does it,

11:28.855 --> 11:30.774
it isn't wrong.

11:32.692 --> 11:34.694
Do you believe that?

11:35.862 --> 11:40.283
<i>The Feds called me, Millie,
they're looking for you.</i>

11:40.283 --> 11:41.785
<i>What did you do?</i>

11:49.126 --> 11:51.086
You okay?

11:51.086 --> 11:53.630
Yup.

11:53.630 --> 11:56.299
- Where are you going?
- Just out of the city

11:56.299 --> 11:57.384
for a bit to retrieve

11:57.384 --> 11:59.052
some of Klaus Rhinehart's
investment papers.

11:59.052 --> 12:01.054
- Nothing exciting.
- Okay, I'll go with you.

12:02.514 --> 12:05.183
Look, I can't stay here all day.
I'll go crazy.

12:06.852 --> 12:08.228
Come on, then.

12:09.813 --> 12:10.814
<i>There are
two Nazi sympathizers</i>

12:10.814 --> 12:12.691
living in this town.

12:12.691 --> 12:14.818
If the Crow was coming here
to see Hitler,

12:14.818 --> 12:17.404
I bet these two are
the gatekeepers.

12:17.404 --> 12:19.072
They own an antique store.

12:19.072 --> 12:21.575
The two of you will pose
as newlyweds,

12:21.575 --> 12:23.535
and I will be
your interior designer.

12:23.535 --> 12:25.537
Why couldn't you
play my husband?

12:25.537 --> 12:27.205
An audience would never believe

12:27.205 --> 12:30.459
such a beautiful woman
being married to this...

12:30.459 --> 12:33.545
gorgeous, gorgeous man.

12:33.545 --> 12:36.131
I love antiquing.

12:36.131 --> 12:37.424
You ever been to the Berkshires?

12:37.424 --> 12:39.176
There's this tiny place
in Lenox...

12:39.176 --> 12:41.428
Oh, my God,
like, the cutest lamps.

12:41.428 --> 12:44.097
You all right?

12:44.097 --> 12:46.141
Yeah, I'm golden. Peachy.

12:46.141 --> 12:48.560
Teflon. Teflon.

12:48.560 --> 12:50.395
Teflonny Flash.

12:50.395 --> 12:53.231
Baby, come on.

12:56.526 --> 12:58.361
You're fucking high?

12:58.361 --> 12:59.571
Just a little pick-me-up
for the time change.

12:59.571 --> 13:00.489
Again, Lonny?

13:00.489 --> 13:01.781
Okay, fuck you.

13:01.781 --> 13:03.116
Again?

13:03.116 --> 13:04.784
You could've
fucked all of this up.

13:04.784 --> 13:05.994
Put us all in danger.

13:05.994 --> 13:07.871
When did you even start
with this shit?

13:07.871 --> 13:10.916
Do you know what I am putting
on the line to be here?

13:10.916 --> 13:13.210
What I am risking?
Why'd you even fucking come

13:13.210 --> 13:14.836
to Argentina?!

13:14.836 --> 13:16.880
Because of you, huh.

13:16.880 --> 13:19.549
Because you were coming!

13:19.549 --> 13:22.219
And I started with this shit

13:22.219 --> 13:24.638
when you left, okay?!

13:24.638 --> 13:26.348
Okay?!

13:30.602 --> 13:31.770
Lonny!

13:32.812 --> 13:34.856
Lonny!

13:35.899 --> 13:37.984
<i>And how can you be
sure it was him that you saw?</i>

13:37.984 --> 13:40.403
That it was this Mr...

13:40.403 --> 13:41.738
Von Staub.

13:41.738 --> 13:43.782
Because,

13:43.782 --> 13:46.117
Mr. Attorney General,

13:46.117 --> 13:48.787
my eyes can't forget

13:48.787 --> 13:51.456
the face of a man
who murdered children.

13:51.456 --> 13:55.126
- Ms. Apfelbaum...
- Ms. Apfelbaum. I know.

13:55.126 --> 13:57.087
We've been to other offices

13:57.087 --> 14:00.549
just like this one,
all high-ranking officials,

14:00.549 --> 14:02.759
and they all say the same thing.

14:02.759 --> 14:04.636
Well, I don't need to hear

14:04.636 --> 14:07.013
another patronizing rejection

14:07.013 --> 14:09.015
from a man so busy,

14:09.015 --> 14:12.227
he has no time to investigate

14:12.227 --> 14:13.937
crimes against the Jews.

14:22.696 --> 14:24.990
She's a feisty one.

14:24.990 --> 14:28.451
Yes, she always has been.

14:28.451 --> 14:30.537
Look, Louie,
I'm sorry about her,

14:30.537 --> 14:33.582
but thank you for your time.

14:33.582 --> 14:35.959
I'll look into it.

14:35.959 --> 14:37.627
What?

14:38.670 --> 14:40.046
I'll investigate it.

14:40.046 --> 14:42.841
What? Oh, no,
that's all right, really.

14:42.841 --> 14:44.509
I'll put my team on it.

14:44.509 --> 14:48.138
Don't. Uh...

14:48.138 --> 14:51.349
She's an old woman.
She's got a lot of pain

14:51.349 --> 14:53.184
and confusion, and, uh,

14:53.184 --> 14:56.021
I don't believe
that there's much truth

14:56.021 --> 14:57.647
in what she says.

14:57.647 --> 15:00.150
I don't want to waste your time,

15:00.150 --> 15:01.484
but she's a friend,

15:01.484 --> 15:05.989
so I-I-I just wanted her
to feel heard.

15:05.989 --> 15:07.240
I understand.

15:07.240 --> 15:09.576
Thank you, Louis.

15:11.119 --> 15:13.705
<i>I was so sure</i>

15:13.705 --> 15:16.875
that your friends,
that your connections, that...

15:16.875 --> 15:18.418
- Uh-huh.
- ...the senators,

15:18.418 --> 15:21.630
the congressmen,
the attorney general...

15:21.630 --> 15:22.922
Nothing, we got nothing.

15:22.922 --> 15:24.883
No one believes us.

15:24.883 --> 15:29.137
Never again, we said,
never again.

15:29.137 --> 15:31.056
I am not going to stop.

15:31.056 --> 15:33.350
You're not gonna let this go,
are you?

15:33.350 --> 15:36.353
I can't. Can you?

15:41.900 --> 15:44.152
What if we did it ourselves?

15:47.906 --> 15:50.700
We get a team,

15:50.700 --> 15:53.328
and we do it ourselves.

15:56.414 --> 15:58.667
This is the girl
you're going to marry?

15:58.667 --> 16:00.293
One who travels halfway

16:00.293 --> 16:02.587
across the world
because she read a name

16:02.587 --> 16:05.757
on a fucking telephone pad?

16:05.757 --> 16:08.093
She's clearly unhinged.

16:10.053 --> 16:11.680
What?

16:11.680 --> 16:13.390
She's actually brilliant,

16:13.390 --> 16:16.351
and if I call off our plans,

16:16.351 --> 16:18.103
she's gonna grow suspicious.

16:18.103 --> 16:19.521
She's gonna find out
what we're up to.

16:19.521 --> 16:21.356
So, lunch, the three of us.

16:21.356 --> 16:24.484
What? You think
I'm happy about this?

16:24.484 --> 16:25.944
I asked Mindy
to pretend to be you,

16:25.944 --> 16:27.320
but she's recuperating in bed,

16:27.320 --> 16:28.697
watching Argentinian
soap operas.

16:28.697 --> 16:30.281
You like this girl?

16:31.950 --> 16:35.704
I love this girl.
She's gonna be my wife.

16:35.704 --> 16:38.456
Then I'm not breaking bread
with her.

16:38.456 --> 16:41.459
If you love this girl,
you will tell her that you lied

16:41.459 --> 16:43.545
about your great-aunt

16:43.545 --> 16:45.004
and that you're actually here

16:45.004 --> 16:47.090
with another girl,
having a fling,

16:47.090 --> 16:49.592
and that you're calling off
the wedding.

16:49.592 --> 16:51.761
Boom. Done. Over.

16:51.761 --> 16:54.305
She's going to be
my family, Chava.

16:54.305 --> 16:55.598
She's gonna be yours.

16:55.598 --> 16:58.685
She's coming over
for lunch, and then

16:58.685 --> 17:00.937
she's gonna fly home
and not suspect a thing,

17:00.937 --> 17:03.523
and then we'll find Hitler
and we'll kill him,

17:03.523 --> 17:05.775
and then I hang it up.

17:05.775 --> 17:07.944
I fly back to Paris,
marry Clara,

17:07.944 --> 17:10.405
grow old, boring,
and happy together.

17:10.405 --> 17:11.948
And that's what happens.

17:11.948 --> 17:13.533
That's what happens for me.

17:13.533 --> 17:16.161
No. That's what happens for Sam.

17:16.161 --> 17:17.996
It's not what happens for you.

17:17.996 --> 17:21.541
You knew about me
even after she died,

17:21.541 --> 17:24.252
and you still never reached out.

17:24.252 --> 17:26.755
This is the least
that you can do.

17:29.132 --> 17:30.258
I'll make chicken.

17:30.258 --> 17:31.760
I'll make a reservation.

17:31.760 --> 17:33.094
That's not how she meets family.

17:33.094 --> 17:36.306
I'm making chicken.

17:39.726 --> 17:41.519
Chicken it is.

18:25.396 --> 18:27.357
What are we gonna do, Biz?

18:27.357 --> 18:29.692
I'll tell you
what we're gonna do.

18:29.692 --> 18:32.862
We're gonna feed 'em
some bullets on Mars.

18:40.703 --> 18:42.163
Cut.

18:42.163 --> 18:45.250
Very nice.
Okay, we're moving on.

18:45.250 --> 18:47.836
Great take.

18:47.836 --> 18:50.338
All right. I think we got it.

18:50.338 --> 18:52.090
I'm gonna be in my trailer.

18:53.424 --> 18:56.427
I think we got that.
That was a great take.

18:56.427 --> 18:58.263
"Bullets on Mars."

19:03.560 --> 19:06.062
Fuck off.

19:06.062 --> 19:07.146
Fuck.

19:10.441 --> 19:12.110
No, no.

19:12.110 --> 19:14.070
- The fuck?
- Get out.

19:14.070 --> 19:15.488
Come on.

19:15.488 --> 19:17.532
Get out.

19:19.492 --> 19:22.287
The fuck? Who the fuck are you?

19:22.287 --> 19:24.289
Who the fuck are you?

19:24.289 --> 19:25.456
You're a mess.

19:25.456 --> 19:27.041
You belong in an outhouse,

19:27.041 --> 19:28.668
- you schmuck.
- I'm calling security.

19:28.668 --> 19:30.253
- Get out of here.
- Aah! Fuck.

